<p><a href="#sdfootnote69anc" name="sdfootnote69sym">69</a> Barthes, “Rhetoric of the Image”: 44.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote70anc" name="sdfootnote70sym">70</a> Thomas Demand in: “A Conversation between Alexander Kluge and Thomas Demand.” In Serpentine Gallery (ed.) <em>Thomas Demand</em>. (London, Munich: Serpentine Gallery/ Schirmer/Mosel, 2006): 56.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote71anc" name="sdfootnote71sym">71</a> Marcoci, "Paper Moon": 26.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote72anc" name="sdfootnote72sym">72</a> This phrase is borrowed from Alexander Kluge, who said about Demand’s work: “You could just as well say that we see the spectres of history left behind. It looks ghostly and yet realistic.” (Alexander Kluge in: “A Conversation between Alexander Kluge and Thomas Demand”: 71.)</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote73anc" name="sdfootnote73sym">73</a> Foster hints at this positive effect of the archive when he closes his essays with the observation that archival art shows a "desire to turn belatedness into becomingness, to recoup failed visions in art, literature, philosophy, and everyday life into possible scenarios of alternative kinds of social relations, to transform the no-place of the archive into the no-place of a utopia ... This move to turn “excavation sites” into “construction sites” is welcome in another way too: it suggests a shift away from a melancholic culture that views the historical as little more than the traumatic.” (Foster, “Archival Impulse”: 22.)</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote74anc" name="sdfootnote74sym">74</a> Ralph Rugoff, “Introduction,” in Ralph Rugoff (ed.), <em>Scene of the Crime</em>. (Cambridge, Mass., London: MIT Press/ Hammer Museum, 1997): 18-19.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote75anc" name="sdfootnote75sym">75</a> Krauss, “Notes on the Index. Part 2”: 65.</p>
